# Euclid Example: Set Theory and Logic

This example demonstrates set theory and logic operations in Euclid.

## Set Notation

Empty set: emptyset
Element of: element_of(x, A)
Subset: subset(A, B)
Union: union(A, B)
Intersection: intersection(A, B)

## Comparison Operators

Less than: lt(a, b) means a < b
Greater than: gt(a, b) means a > b
Less than or equal: leq(a, b) means a <= b
Greater than or equal: geq(a, b) means a >= b
Approximately equal: approx(a, b) means a ≈ b
Not equal: neq(a, b) means a ≠ b
Equivalent: equiv(a, b) means a ≡ b

## Logical Operators

AND: P AND Q
OR: P OR Q
NOT: NOT(P)
Implies: implies(P, Q)
If and only if: iff(P, Q)

## Quantifiers

For all: forall(x, P(x))
There exists: exists(x, P(x))

## Logic Examples

De Morgan's law: equiv(NOT(P AND Q), NOT(P) OR NOT(Q))
Contrapositive: equiv(implies(P, Q), implies(NOT(Q), NOT(P)))

## Number Theory

Greatest common divisor: gcd(a, b)
Least common multiple: lcm(a, b)
Modulo: mod(a, b)
Plus-minus: pm(a, b)
Times symbol: times(a, b)
Division symbol: div(a, b)

## Floor and Ceiling

Floor: floor(x)
Ceiling: ceil(x)
Absolute value: abs(x)

## Arrows

Right arrow: rightarrow
Left arrow: leftarrow
Double right arrow: Rightarrow
Maps to: mapsto

## Dot Sequences

Horizontal dots: ldots
Centered dots: cdots
Vertical dots: vdots
Diagonal dots: ddots

## Proof Notation

Therefore: therefore
Because: because
QED: qed

## Geometry

Perpendicular: perp
Parallel: parallel
Angle: angle
Triangle: triangle
Congruent: cong
Similar: sim
